A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and they believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices, which record every mile driven and report the information to the authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning agencies to overhaul the outdated system of financing U.S. roads.
The normally rather boring field of road planning has suddenly ignited an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied with environmental groups and are advocating that the government use the little boxes to record the miles driven  and possibly where they were driven  and then use the information for tax returns.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of concerns about privacy.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently looking at how they can move to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next ten years.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
It's a must for our country.
"It's not something we're just going to use", said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which plans to record the miles driven by all California motorists in the state by 2025.
The way we pay these taxes is going to change.
The technology is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded by the taxes Americans pay on the pump pile, is bankrupt.
But in America, they don't get as much gas as they used to.
Cars use less gas.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 euro cents per litre) has not been raised for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax by even a penny at high fuel prices.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable", says Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
'This is the most sensible alternative in the long term', he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mileage-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is appealing to urban liberals, for the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in a way that reduces traffic jams and climate-damaging emissions.
California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state's ambitious, legally-enforced climate change goals.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Even the freelance marketers at the Reason Foundation are excited by the idea of letting drivers pay for the distance traveled.
"This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole", explains Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former US transportation secretaries who in a 2011 report urged Congress to move towards mile-based billing.
The US Senate approved last year a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push, responding to the concerns of rural MPs, who represent people who often have to travel many miles to work or to the city in their daily lives.
Nevertheless, several states and large cities are moving in this direction on their own initiative.
The most committed is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon be paying the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one of these, too.
Illinois is testing it on a limited scale with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently looking into how to implement the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, motorists were skeptical that the government could track their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem", explains Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test began, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices".
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states now looking for affordable technology that will allow the state to track miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
Khan said that would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some government agencies to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company didn't originally pitch in to help states tax motorists.
Rather, it was aimed at establishing a foothold in an emerging market for motor insurance where drivers are expected to pay on the basis of miles driven.
But the devices she tested are also of interest to road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and location are not recorded", explained Ryan Morrison, managing director of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programmes have been seriously flawed.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways of doing this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving motorists a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose not to use the device at all and instead pay a flat rate based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to sell the concept to a distrustful public by equipping the devices with more functions rather than fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials are planning to develop a tax-paying device that will allow people to pay parking fees, insure themselves on miles driven, and collect real-time speed data from other vehicles so that drivers can avoid traffic jams.
Motorists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system, according to a city planning document.
Some road planners wonder, though, whether all the talk about paying per mile is just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel taxes.
An additional one-off fee or annual levy could be imposed on drivers of hybrid or other low-fuel vehicles, so that they too pay a fair share.
"There is no need for surgery if aspirin is enough", explains Randy Rentschler, Commissioner for Legislation and Public Affairs.
If we do that, we're going to make hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and countless other things.
