ESA decides on major space missions: missions for billions
Distant planets, gravitational waves or black holes - Experts at the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects they plan to launch in the next few years.
30 proposals were to be selected, five are still in the race.
Far away worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1,000 planets around other stars.
Whether there is life on some of them, no one knows.
The choice is hard: Should we look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for planets like Earth, and maybe find life outside of Earth?
These are the questions that the European Space Agency (ESA) is asking itself.
For their Cosmic Vision programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that will make a major contribution to research.
The budget for such "L" missions is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space exploration met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were debated, five of which have now been narrowly voted on.
The Commission has also been involved in the preparation of the draft budget for the period from 1 January 1997 to 31 December 1998.
A final decision by the Scientific Program Committee is expected in the next few days.
ESA has selected four key questions to answer for the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, which was launched in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact process of star formation from large gas clouds - and thus the formation of planets orbiting them - is still a matter of proverbial obscurity.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has a planet, what are the conditions under which life can arise?
To answer that question, the Cheops space telescope is scheduled to launch in 2017 to study more closely 500 known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity.
The possibilities are limited, however, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres to look for "biomarkers", gases that are considered indicators of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately designed to shed light on the conditions for the origin of life.
A key factor is the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the radiation it emits with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied in an exemplary way.
With the Solar Orbiter, ESA has already approved an M-class mission (with a budget of about half a billion euros) for this purpose.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and will closely observe the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the evolution of the solar system.
ESA is planning the first of three L-missions under the Cosmic Vision programme.
The Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is assigned to study the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europa, Callisto, and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and to see if the laws of nature that we know are still valid there.
There may also be deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory that would unite all known laws of nature.
How did the universe come into existence and what is it made of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was formed by the Big Bang.
In addition to the familiar matter that makes up stars, planets, and living things like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters together, and dark energy, which accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, scientists do not know what physical laws were in effect in the first few fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy are made of.
With Euclid, ESA has already approved an M-mission, which is scheduled to launch in 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe is to study the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus making it possible to draw conclusions about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection procedure.
The best chance of being approved as an L-mission, according to many experts, is the E-Lisa, a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand this as changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
The scientists behind the project hope that Elisa could do it.
The mission will involve a detector consisting of two or three probes, which will be stationed in space.
Unlike the machines on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that formed during the Big Bang, providing new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called Athena, which will explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which will detect and study Earth-like planets.
Proposals for the return of samples from Mars, the exploration of the Moon, Venus and asteroids, and solar physics have already been rejected.
