Basharat Ditta, 42, has passed information to the underworld giant Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid his secret drug addiction might come out
He was sentenced to three years in prison by Liverpool Crown Court
A well-known criminal defense attorney who warned a drug lord about a major police investigation because he feared his secret drug addiction might be exposed was sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided underworld giant Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about investigations into his drug trafficking activities after he was compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
The "top-notch" criminal lawyer, nicknamed "Bash", was arrested in his home in 2011 after police monitored Scarborough, which he had represented in a previous drug case.
Officers watched Scarborough, 32, deliver three bags of cocaine to the lawyer's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a bar council dinner with colleagues.
The investigation revealed that Ditta regularly used Class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Over a period of eight months between January and August 2011, he unlawfully sought information on the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his associates.
All four suspects were then under police surveillance as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They were later arrested along with 32 others after police seized £1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine and £200,000 in cash during a series of house searches.
Ditta, 42, passed information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction might become public.
Ditta, who works for Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn, was found guilty at Liverpool Crown Court today after a three-week trial on two counts of obstruction of justice.
He admitted to possession of cocaine in an earlier interview.
The lawyer was convicted after police discovered in their investigation of Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and place the 60 percent drugs in a black golf glove under the lawyer's trash can.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough was on the phone regularly with Ditta, who was at dinner at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park.
The lawyer went back home, got the drugs, and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
It was revealed at the trial that Ditta was a 'regular user' of cocaine after tests detected Class A drugs in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied taking cocaine, saying he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client, and claimed their discussion was under "lawyer confidentiality".
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a series of credit cards, but they were secured and a hair sample was taken.
During police questioning, he stated that he had an office at his private address as well as at his workplace and that clients would call him at home for legal matters.
It was revealed in court that he had called major drug traffickers, some of whom he had represented before, for significant arrests and had informed investigators what they knew about them.
The prosecutor Anne Whyte said: "A criminal lawyer should know better than anyone else that you are not breaking the law".
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal defense attorney by getting too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, for he was the advocate for these persons.
But this went far beyond the boundaries of a normal lawyer-client relationship.
He obstructed the police investigation as much as possible so that they could continue their criminal activities.
Mr Ditta has thus brought his professional reputation into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any wrongdoing, claiming: "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass information to Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, but do it immediately".
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said: "Mr Ditta made the leap from being a criminal lawyer to a criminal the moment he started buying drugs from organised criminals".
His cocaine addiction led to a hopeless compromise and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organized crime who commissioned him to obtain valuable information on police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and maintain public trust and confidence.
Ditta has betrayed that trust and tried to hide behind the facade of his profession.
Lancashire's Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation into Ditta, which also led to a conviction in three cases for cocaine possession and obstruction of justice, which underlines our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and show that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We'll find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty to conspiracy to traffic heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other persons involved in drug trafficking were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug offences.
