And one that has come so far in the years that it already looks like a fossil: I first heard the "independence means passport control" ending at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the European whistle?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
This is the real news in Europe: the great plan for European unification, conceived after the war, has been put on hold.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project has officially died.
All over the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro as the common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year, won almost five million votes in the September parliamentary elections, effectively expelling the Free Democrats (the British equivalent of the Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, is proving to be a turning point.
The strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the straitjacket imposed on the national economies by the adherence to the single currency, have led many people to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments creating excessive budget deficits  this was the case only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pegged its members to exchange rates that are favourable to German exporters  and German politicians would like to keep it that way.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, southern Europe is left with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared with Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public expenditure, with the encouragement of Berlin.
The current budgetary and monetary problems are the result of a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the 'green energy' directives enacted by Brussels, a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers, European industry is paying twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we saw in Grangemouth.
All the wage-setting systems in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is rising, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and to bring Paris to the same level as Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, which is a problem for the battered French economy.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a decisive by-election, pushing the ruling Socialists to third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the votes  a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right-wing spectrum would automatically mean advantages for the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among white working-class French?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community monetary bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections, and this is very possible, then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will converge on the abolition of the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be standing alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where does Scotland stand in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the final analysis) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes telling Berlin and Brussels where to go.
I think Scotland could do very well in a looser European Union if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise we should consider doing the same as Norway and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  remarkably  the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and implemented) cuts, which were blamed on Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to choose independence now, only to be forced into a policy of austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
