African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts, studies show.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible for
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic is a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter starts to grow breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz said that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and represent a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents", said Kaplowitz, "which is not usually a sign that puberty is fast approaching".
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and arm hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
However, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (the occurrence of the first menstrual period) over the past 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
"When breast development begins, it takes at least two to three years to menarche", said Kaplowitz, who also authored the book "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Managing This Common Problem".
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the onset of puberty, but it is 'premature' when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates, which a pediatrician can monitor closely.
If progress is made more rapidly, tests by an endochronologist may be indicated to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can ultimately lead to stunting and thus to short growth in adults.
Recommendations for medication or hormone therapy are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reserved about medication, but admits: Repressing puberty can ease behavioural problems and girls' feelings of being different from their peers.
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have their period.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygiene side", Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock", recalls a woman whose daughter had her first birthday at the age of ten.
Even though there were early signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home from school scared and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are the cause.
Boys, like girls, come into puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the obesity epidemic.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine, which established a link between body fat and the onset of puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend toward full-blown early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the subject.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in infants and young children.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty", said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean having to have a conversation sooner than expected", Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need reassurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs sooner than expected.
