Scientists have shed more light on the relationship between a dog's tail wagging and its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs waved their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), whereas nervous dogs waved their tails to the left.
But now scientists say that other dogs can sense and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known that in humans, the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that elicit positive or negative emotions".
Here we've tried to look at this in other species.
He also noticed that in dogs, just as in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left hemisphere and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral wagging of their fellow species, the researchers monitored the animals as they watched these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the quadrupeds and analyzed their behavior.
We'll probably soon understand why the tail moves in one direction and the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs films with dogs either in a natural version or in a silhouette to eliminate other distracting aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right".
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog move its tail to the right (from the waving dog's perspective), they were completely relaxed.
But if the tail was predominantly to the left (again from the dog's perspective, which is waving), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, these movements are not intended to communicate with each other.
Rather, he believes that the dogs would have learned by experience which movements they should be concerned about and which not.
He said: "If you have various encounters with other dogs and wagging your tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences".
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers to better understand their pets' emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and visiting fellow at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Medicine, said that this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they see an aggressive dog, and to the right when they see a happy dog.
Another study at the University of Victoria in Canada found that "dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail is waving to the left rather than the right, rather than becoming restless".
He said that the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the different studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
"While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain hemispheres are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined", and dogs are no exception, Bradshaw said.
But since its behavior is easy to record, it probably won't take long to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction and sometimes in the other.
