I recognize the great and multifaceted things that Obama has accomplished, from passing the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the withdrawal of the military from Iraq to ending the forced silence on homosexuality in the military and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I too believe that the partisan tactic of blockade has overturned too many of the efforts that our nation should have made to move forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name just a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times to colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end of my explanatory efforts.
I've reached a point of political despair.
The Republican policy of blockade cannot explain why it is allowed to listen to foreign heads of state or to kill innocent children by drones overseas.
It can't explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are punished for exposing government misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why the limits on public funding and spending are being circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the findings of a report that the White House's efforts to calm the media are the most "aggressive" since the Nixon administration.
And finally, it doesn't excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if this is what I should have expected.
I wonder if I should have understood at 18 that government work could be at odds with her previous political campaigns.
Clearly, the House is not a predictable course, with an opposition party and random events like the Newtown massacre shaping the public debate.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to have been largely elected by the government itself.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unfinished alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressures of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had been hearing for so long.
