For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father pass out and travel to hospitals that did not have the resources to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but then an inflammation developed that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma there that would affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon", says Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy", says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwell's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the United States has one doctor for every 413 persons.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's health expenditures are private.
"The only problem they have is poverty", says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffered made Bwelle determined to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others are forced to get into minibuses and drive over unfortified terrain with their strapped medical equipment on the roof to the villages that need help.
Things don't always work out.
On more than one occasion, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing, and the best lodging the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a cause for celebration and Bwelle  with his broad smile and boundless energy  is happy to join in the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team starts examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip", said Bwelle.
They come from a 60 kilometre radius around the village of  and that is on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates  a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
At night, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations are usually carried out in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The group's generator powers the lighting for the O.R. and disinfection equipment, and Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a strenuous schedule, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They're drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work", says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team heads back to the city, tired but proud of the work they've done.
The group  a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students  performed 700 free surgeries last year and know that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he had received on a hernia now enabled him to work again.
"This changes the future of my family", the man said.
In addition to weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, Bwelle says, he finances 60% of his charity work, the rest coming from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping", says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Bwell's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go to these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe to support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience that they would never get back home.
"We can be in surgeries, helping to pump blood or holding instruments for Dr. Bwelle", explains O'Malley.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon and often bring donated sanitary equipment.
Once in Yaoundé, however, Bwelle takes care of the accommodation, transportation, and guidance.
"He is without a doubt a hero", says O'Malley.
