Tourism: The Descent to the Romans
A wastewater canal from Roman times has been preserved below Cologne, at a length of about 120 metres.
If you visit Cologne, you won't pass the cathedral.
The two towers rise to a height of some 157 meters, making it the second-tallest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who marvel at the two filigree towers of the church know that there is much to discover under the dome.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts off in a very unimpressive way: "We start in the underground garage", says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a city that was car-friendly, so only the small remains of the old city walls remained.
Most of the parking lot users are therefore rushing past the Roman remains today and just parking their car.
But if you look closely, you will discover an archaeological site in Deck D2 that is separated by metal bars.
The ruins are about five meters high and are made of merchants' size stones.
"They are remnants of the Roman city walls built in the second half of the first century A.D"., says Schulze.
Before returning to the light of day, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look into a dark, 50 feet [15 m] deep shaft.
This is the well of the old cathedral, which, unfortunately, is hardly noticed.
The next stop on the tour is the Praetorium, where the participants descend into the depths.
We are here to witness the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Prefect of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in plain German means "City of Roman Law and City of the Agrippinenses, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the cult of the Emperor".
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the hall of the exhibition, a tunnel leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want", Schulze encourages the guests.
Schulze has one more surprise.
After getting the key from the register, he leads the group to a 16-foot-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the mikvah, a ritual Jewish bath", he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep in the ground to get to the groundwater that was essential for ritual washing.
To this day, the lower end of the mikveh, whose origins date back to the eighth century, is marked by varying water levels due to the changing level of the Rhine.
The mikveh will be part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
But it will be a few years before completion.
