John Kerry admits in unprecedented fashion that US espionage has gone "unreasonably far"
John Kerry made an unexpected admission indicating a softening of the US's defensive stance on its surveillance programmes, saying that in certain cases the spying had 'gone unreasonably far'.
The Secretary of State also admitted that he shared responsibility with Barack Obama for turning on "Autopilot" when the explosive revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA's spying activities became public.
The leaked information has sent the US government into a diplomatic firestorm of outrage from its allies.
In a video-transmitted speech at the Open Government Conference in London, Kerry said: "There is no question that the president and I and others in government have been told of some things that have gone on autopilot, simply because the capability was there, which goes back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, to 9/11.
He was the first senior member of the US government to admit that US espionage had crossed a line, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said: 'In some cases this has gone too far.'
The president is determined to bring clarity, and therefore is conducting a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons will not be compromised in this trial.
But Kerry insisted that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance efforts had saved many lives.
He added: "We are dealing with a new world in which people are ready to blow themselves up".
There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we have been told in advance of such plans.
Meanwhile, US lawmakers will travel to Europe to allay concerns about alleged US espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the US on counterterrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to European Parliament members and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terror organizations because of frustration with the National Security Agency's surveillance.
"It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans stay on board our joint efforts against terrorism", Murphy, a first-time Democrat in the Senate and chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
I'm also going to Europe to make it clear that we need to continue to work together on counterterrorism despite their anger over the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe have strained relations with some US allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were false and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents shared by Snowden that the NSA had been monitoring the cell phones of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state around the world.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended spying on allies as necessary, saying it was common on both sides.
In all the commotion, Murphy said his office was preparing for the congressional trip that was scheduled to take place this year, and he hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other Members who will be attending will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact route is still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relations, he also spoke of some very serious words.
He said European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of spying programs they themselves have been using for years.
"While we can change our surveillance programmes to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also accept that we are not the only ones spying", Murphy said.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is scheduled to travel to the Middle East and Poland over the weekend to deal with the resentment over US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, and US surveillance activities.
